to compile type:
	make

run with:
	./spaced [options] <sequence file>

options:
	 -h: print this help and exit
	 -f <file>: specify file containing patterns that should be used
	 -p <file>: specify file in which used patterns will be saved afterwards
	 -o <file>: specify the output file name (default: <sequence file> + .dmat)
	 -k <integer>: specify pattern weight
	 -l <integer>: specify pattern don't care positions
	 -n <integer>: specify amount of patterns you want to generate
	 -t <integer>: specify amount of threads that should be used (default: number of sequences, fastest)
	 -s: save single matrices as well as the combined matrix
	 -v: fixed pattern lengths (default: variable)
	 -quiet: no status messages (errors and progress will still be printed)

_______________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Scientific publications using Spaced Words should cite:

    C.-A. Leimeister, M. Boden, S. Horwege, S. Lindner, B. Morgenstern (2014)
    Fast alignment-free sequence comparison using spaced-word frequencies
    Bioinformatics, DOI: 10.1093/bioinformatics/btu177 (http://bioinformatics.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2014/04/03/bioinformatics.btu177)
    
    
    S. Horwege, S. Linder, M. Boden, K. Hatje, M. Kollmar, C.-A. Leimeister, B. Morgenstern (2014)
    Spaced words and kmacs: fast alignment-free sequence comparison based on inexact word matches
    Nuc. Acids Research 42, W7-W11 (http://nar.oxfordjournals.org/content/42/W1/W7.abstract)

   
    B. Morgenstern, B. Zhu, S. Horwege, C.-A. Leimeister (2014)
    Estimating evolutionary distances from spaced-word matches
    In: Proceedings WABI 2014, Lecture Notes in Bioinformatics, pp. 161-173
    Springer Verlag
